      "writtenOn": "2020-10-29T20:15:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here\u0027s the launder requirements:\n\n- YES: the pointer p represents the address A of a byte in memory\n- YES: an object X is located at the address A\n- YES: X is within its lifetime\n- NOT SURE: the type of X is the same as T, ignoring cv-qualifiers at every level\n- YES: every byte that would be reachable through the result is reachable through p\n\n(If all are true, then std::launder(p) returns a value of type T* that points to the object X. Otherwise, the behavior is undefined.)\n\nI\u0027m not confident about the type-sameness case because at this point in the code, we haven\u0027t done anything with fStorage yet; it\u0027s just a char[]. I would intuitively think they\u0027re not the same until we placement-new into it.\n\nHowever, I tried using the launder call after the placement-new copy/move loop, and it caused the asserts to fire again.\n\nWhat do you think?",
      "parentUuid": "6d61c836_54688291",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 56
      },
      "revId": "9d9bf68fb45540391be1309bae40b3110baef4e8",
