      "side": 1,
      "message": "What do we do about GCC users who are not using C++17 yet?",
      "revId": "9d9bf68fb45540391be1309bae40b3110baef4e8",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "54535021_9f8aa327",
        "filename": "include/private/SkTArray.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 505,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-10-29T20:15:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We already require that C++17 language support must be enabled, and I don\u0027t know why a GCC user would enable C++17 but then revert to C++14 for their standard library; I know Chrome does this, but I wouldn\u0027t expect it from a typical codebase.\n\nAssuming the situation did occur in the wild (--std\u003dc++17 without std::launder), they would need to compile in -O2 -fno-strict-aliasing to work around the bug, I guess. I don\u0027t know of any way to fix the issue for them. It\u0027s possible that this client would already running into inexplicable errors, or maybe our usage of SkSTArray is limited enough that we don\u0027t actually encounter this issue anywhere outside of tests.",
      "parentUuid": "c85f09be_8d0c91bd",
      "revId": "9d9bf68fb45540391be1309bae40b3110baef4e8",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
